TL;DR — I built a multi-agent research pipeline on the Anthropic API. Feed it a topic → four research agents search the web in parallel, then other agents flag conflicting sources and write a cited report. Here’s how it works, and what it cost.
Previously, I built a tiny Claude Code clone to understand what tools and the agentic loop are. I did a write-up about it. If you’re not familiar with these concepts, I recommend reading that first. Today, I am going to show how to create a research pipeline that produces high-quality reports, given only one brief topic and the costs I was billed for.
What will you learn after reading it?

• How to extract data in the desired output format using the Messages API

• How to build pipelines using tools and delegate subtasks to agents

• How to save API costs during development
4 agents made the research flow possible:

• Coordinator agent — splits a brief, vague topic into 4 subtopics for research

• Research agents — spawned in parallel to crawl the web for information and output trustworthy claims with sources and confidence score

• Analysis agent — runs to flag data conflicts (PERIODIC_DATA vs REAL conflicts)

• Synthesizer agent — writes a well-structured Markdown research report from validated findings
Press enter or click to view image in full size

The research pipeline schemaPipeline implementation
Step 1: Coordinator
The topic that I’ve chosen is “JS runtime wars: Node vs Bun vs Deno”. Let’s ask the pipeline to prepare a report for it!
The core function is “extractStructured” and the main idea of it is to extract data from the model in a format that our app requires. This function takes a custom tool definition, a prompt, and other arguments, and forces the model to use the provided tool to pass data in a well-formatted way. Once the model generates an answer for the prompt, it calls the tool we provided. The input that the model supplies is based on the ZOD schema we requested. Before accepting the model output, the app validates it programmatically using zod to validate the shape. The app has 3 retries to make sure the LLM produces the correct format.
export async function extractStructured<T>(args: {
call: ModelCall;
cfg: AgentConfig;
system: string;
userText: string;
toolName: string;
toolDescription: string;
schema: z.ZodType<T>;
inputSchema: Record<string, unknown>;
maxAttempts?: number;
}): Promise<{ data: T; messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] }> {
const maxAttempts = args.maxAttempts ?? 3;
const tools = [
{
name: args.toolName,
description: args.toolDescription,
input_schema: args.inputSchema,
},
] as Anthropic.MessageCreateParams["tools"];
const messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [
{ role: "user", content: args.userText },
]; for (let attempt = 1; attempt <= maxAttempts; attempt++) {
const resp = await args.call(
buildParams(args.cfg, {
system: args.system,
messages,
tools,
toolChoice: { type: "tool", name: args.toolName },
}),
);
messages.push({ role: "assistant", content: resp.content });
if (resp.stop_reason === "max_tokens") {
throw new MaxTokensError(args.toolName, args.cfg.maxTokens, messages);
}
const block = resp.content.find(
(b): b is Anthropic.ToolUseBlock =>
b.type === "tool_use" && b.name === args.toolName,
);
if (!block) continue;
const v = validate(args.schema, block.input);
if (v.ok) return { data: v.data, messages };
messages.push({
role: "user",
content: [
{
type: "tool_result",
tool_use_id: block.id,
is_error: true,
content: `Validation failed:\n${v.issues.join("\n")}\nFix the issues and call ${args.toolName} again.`,
},
],
});
}
throw new Error(
`${args.toolName}: did not produce valid output after ${maxAttempts} attempts`,
);
}
`toolChoice: { type: “tool”, name: args.toolName }` forces the model to use a tool and not generate unstructured prose.
I’ve also added max token error handling for graceful degradation, and a terminal error if the model fails to produce correct data (which almost never happens)
Remember! The pipeline must not fail if some subagents fail the task. It should proceed, but flag the issue.
`args.call` uses `new Anthropic({ timeout: 240_000, maxRetries: 1 }).messages.create(params)` under the hood, and `validate` util looks like:
export function validate<T>(schema: z.ZodType<T>, input: unknown): Validation<T> {
const r = schema.safeParse(input);
if (r.success) return { ok: true, data: r.data };
return {
ok: false,
issues: r.error.issues.map(
(i) => `${i.path.join(".") || "(root)"}: ${i.message}`,
),
};
}Let’s run the first phase — coordinator logic
// planTopic utilexport const COORDINATOR_CONFIG: AgentConfig = {
model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
maxTokens: 2048,
effort: "low", // simple planning task; low effort cuts token spend
};
const PLAN_SYSTEM = `You are the coordinator of a research workflow.
Decompose the research topic into 3-4 focused subtopics.
For each subtopic, give a one-line research brief telling a researcher what to look for.`;
export async function planTopic(
call: ModelCall,
topic: string,
cfg: AgentConfig = COORDINATOR_CONFIG,
): Promise<{ plan: Plan; messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] }> {
const { data, messages } = await extractStructured({
call,
cfg,
system: PLAN_SYSTEM,
userText: `Research topic: ${topic}`,
toolName: "submit_plan",
toolDescription: "Submit the research plan (subtopics + briefs).",
schema: PlanSchema,
inputSchema: jsonSchemaFor(PlanSchema),
});
return { plan: data, messages };
}
// PlanSchema
export const PlanSchema = z.object({
subtopics: z
.array(
z.object({
name: z
.string()
.min(1)
.describe(
"A short, focused subtopic name",
),
brief: z
.string()
.min(1)
.describe(
"A one-line research brief telling a researcher what to look for in this subtopic.",
),
}),
)
.min(1)
});
// jsonSchemaFor util
export function jsonSchemaFor(schema: z.ZodType): Record<string, unknown> {
const js = zodToJsonSchema(schema, { $refStrategy: "none" }) as Record<
string,
unknown
>;
delete js.$schema;
return js;
}
// Coordinator run - where the pipeline starts
...
log("[1/4] Planning research subtopics...");
const { plan, messages: planMsgs } = await planTopic(call, topic);
...
log(` Planned ${plan.subtopics.length} subtopics:`);
plan.subtopics.forEach((s, i) => log(` ${i + 1}. ${s.name}`));
log(` Planning done in ${elapsed(phaseAt)}.`);
...
‘planTopic’ is the coordinator-specific util that calls `extractStructured` providing the tool name, description, and schema. Tool name and description are no-ops here, because `extractStructured` is forced for a tool use, and the most important part here is the schema I provide. The LLM must emit a tool result in that format.
Step 2: Research subagents
This is where things get interesting. We need to run a research agent loop that will gather highly trustworthy information using the built-in Claude ‘web_search’ tool (by means of browsing the Internet) and submit findings in a structured way using a custom tool.
2 tools are to be provided:

• web_search — for Internet access. For the sake of cost optimization, it is allowed to make 2 searches on the web (max_uses)

• submit_findings — to submit results in a structured way
A fixed turn cap keeps iterations bounded so the loop can’t run up cost.
Again, the LLM is forced to call one of the provided tools and not output unnecessary prose.
export async function runResearchLoop(args: {
call: ModelCall;
cfg: AgentConfig;
system: string;
userText: string;
inputSchema: Record<string, unknown>;
maxAttempts?: number;
maxSearches?: number;
maxTurns?: number;
label?: string;
}): Promise<{ findings: Finding[]; messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] }> {
const maxAttempts = args.maxAttempts ?? 3;
const maxTurns = args.maxTurns ?? 8; const searchTool = {
type: "web_search_20260209",
name: "web_search",
max_uses: args.maxSearches ?? 2,
};
const submitTool = {
name: "submit_findings",
description:
"Submit the structured research findings gathered from web search.",
input_schema: args.inputSchema,
};
const messages: Anthropic.MessageParam[] = [
{ role: "user", content: args.userText },
];
let attempts = 0;
let forceSubmit = false;
let containerId: string | undefined;
let turns = 0;
const stage = `research${args.label ? ` [${args.label}]` : ""}`;
while (true) {
if (turns >= maxTurns) throw new LoopBudgetError(stage, turns, messages);
if (turns === maxTurns - 1) forceSubmit = true;
turns += 1;
const resp = await args.call(
buildParams(args.cfg, {
system: args.system,
messages,
tools: [searchTool, submitTool] as Anthropic.MessageCreateParams["tools"],
toolChoice: forceSubmit
? { type: "tool", name: "submit_findings" }
: { type: "any" },
container: containerId, // sonnet and opus spin up a container to run dynamic filtering on it (web search feature not to load the whole webpage to context)
}),
);
if (resp.container?.id) containerId = resp.container.id;
messages.push({ role: "assistant", content: resp.content });
const searches = resp.content.filter(
(b) => b.type === "server_tool_use" && b.name === "web_search",
).length;
if (searches > 0 && args.label) {
log(` [${args.label}] web search ×${searches}`);
}
// pause_turn means: "I started server-side work but paused — re-send and I'll resume." There are pending tool uses sitting in that container, waiting to finish.
if (resp.stop_reason === "pause_turn") {
if (args.label) log(` [${args.label}] resuming (turn ${turns}/${maxTurns})`);
continue;
}
if (resp.stop_reason === "max_tokens") {
throw new MaxTokensError(stage, args.cfg.maxTokens, messages);
}
const submitFindingsToolUse = resp.content.find(
(b): b is Anthropic.ToolUseBlock =>
b.type === "tool_use" && b.name === "submit_findings",
);
if (!submitFindingsToolUse) {
forceSubmit = true;
continue;
}
const v = validate(FindingsPayloadSchema, submitFindingsToolUse.input);
if (v.ok) return { findings: v.data.findings, messages };
if (++attempts >= maxAttempts)
throw new Error(
`research: findings invalid after ${maxAttempts} attempts: ${v.issues.join("; ")}`,
);
messages.push({
role: "user",
content: [
{
type: "tool_result",
tool_use_id: submitFindingsToolUse.id,
is_error: true,
content: `Validation failed:\n${v.issues.join("\n")}\nFix and call submit_findings again.`,
},
],
});
}
}
Max loop and max tokens exceptions are gracefully handled so as not to stop the process.
Once data is prepared, validate it programmatically and submit.
We use ‘web_search’ for Sonnet 4.6, which means Claude uses the dynamic filtering feature for serving the web. Instead of loading the whole site's HTML into the context, it generates a parsing script to fill the valuable information only into the context. These scripts are run on a Linux container, and that’s why we need to pass `containerId`. If we don’t, the API will fail.
Once we have prepared ‘runResearchLoop’ function, let’s define a parent util ‘runResearchAgent’ that will spawn a research agent by calling `runResearchLoop’ and providing the necessary arguments.
export const RESEARCH_CONFIG: AgentConfig = {
model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
maxTokens: 4096,
effort: "medium", // tool-using loop; medium balances search quality vs cost
};const SYSTEM = `You are a research agent investigating ONE subtopic of a larger study.
Search the web for current, credible sources, then call submit_findings with an array of findings.
Rules:
- Return ONLY the 5 most important, well-supported findings. Do not exceed 5. Quality over quantity.
- Every finding MUST cite a real source_url taken from your web_search results. Never invent URLs.
- excerpt MUST be a short verbatim snippet from that source.
- published_date: ISO date the source was published, or null if unknown.
- data_collection_date: when the source's underlying data was gathered
(e.g. a survey field date or benchmark run date), or null if unknown.
This matters: numbers gathered at different times are not contradictions.
- confidence_score: 0..1, how well-supported the claim is.
- Prefer claims with concrete numbers and dates where possible.`;
